WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:19.692 --> 00:00:21.150
DAVID WEITZ: So welcome, everybody.

00:00:21.150 --> 00:00:24.460
We have certain traditions
in this lecture.

00:00:24.460 --> 00:00:27.870
If you haven't been here, I will
teach you about our traditions.

00:00:27.870 --> 00:00:34.270
First of all, you know, these lectures
are associated with a lecture series,

00:00:34.270 --> 00:00:37.810
a class at Harvard.

00:00:37.810 --> 00:00:39.360
It's a science and cooking class.

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:43.320
And so we may see equations.

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:45.255
And if we do, what do we do?

00:00:45.255 --> 00:00:48.510
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:48.510 --> 00:00:51.390
I see only a small fraction
know that we have to do that.

00:00:51.390 --> 00:00:54.690
Everybody has to do that if
you happen to see an equation.

00:00:54.690 --> 00:00:59.850
Also, just to encourage people
to come to these public lectures,

00:00:59.850 --> 00:01:04.170
we have a quiz about the last
lecture, and we give out prizes.

00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:08.940
Where did our prizes-- oh.

00:01:08.940 --> 00:01:11.460
Can we show a prize?

00:01:11.460 --> 00:01:15.717
So it's an apron with
all the equations on it.

00:01:15.717 --> 00:01:21.860
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:21.860 --> 00:01:22.360
OK.

00:01:22.360 --> 00:01:25.630
So those of you who were
here at the last lecture

00:01:25.630 --> 00:01:28.740
will have a little bit of a head
start, but anybody can answer.

00:01:28.740 --> 00:01:31.610
And just raise your hand
as quickly as you can.

00:01:31.610 --> 00:01:33.580
And if I see you first, I'll ask you.

00:01:33.580 --> 00:01:41.446
So from before, why does sparkling water
taste so different from normal water?

00:01:41.446 --> 00:01:43.959
AUDIENCE: It has carbon dioxide.

00:01:43.959 --> 00:01:45.000
DAVID WEITZ: Oh, come on.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:45.660
That's easy.

00:01:45.660 --> 00:01:46.650
Why?

00:01:46.650 --> 00:01:49.620
What does it do?

00:01:49.620 --> 00:01:51.452
Anybody else?

00:01:51.452 --> 00:01:56.853
AUDIENCE: The carbon dioxide comes
up from the-- or through the water.

00:01:56.853 --> 00:01:58.445
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:58.445 --> 00:02:00.480
DAVID WEITZ: I'm going to be tough.

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:01.350
It's carbon dioxide.

00:02:01.350 --> 00:02:01.850
So what?

00:02:01.850 --> 00:02:03.509
AUDIENCE: Makes it acidic.

00:02:03.509 --> 00:02:05.270
DAVID WEITZ: Ah, he wins.

00:02:05.270 --> 00:02:06.680
It's acidic.

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:07.820
So what did we learn?

00:02:07.820 --> 00:02:10.979
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:10.979 --> 00:02:13.378
Do you know what the pH is?

00:02:13.378 --> 00:02:15.050
AUDIENCE: Sorry, I wasn't here for that.

00:02:15.050 --> 00:02:15.716
DAVID WEITZ: Oh.

00:02:15.716 --> 00:02:17.050
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:17.050 --> 00:02:18.790
It's 4.5.

00:02:18.790 --> 00:02:24.040
And it turns out that all good foods are
much more likely to be acidic than they

00:02:24.040 --> 00:02:26.510
are to be basic or even neutral.

00:02:26.510 --> 00:02:29.620
And so that's why.

00:02:29.620 --> 00:02:30.350
So sorry.

00:02:30.350 --> 00:02:32.930
You missed the main point.

00:02:32.930 --> 00:02:36.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:37.730 --> 00:02:38.330
OK.

00:02:38.330 --> 00:02:43.280
Harold talked about tea, and we
had black tea and green tea and--

00:02:43.280 --> 00:02:44.420
AUDIENCE: Oolong.

00:02:44.420 --> 00:02:45.770
DAVID WEITZ: Oolong tea.

00:02:45.770 --> 00:02:46.380
Very good.

00:02:46.380 --> 00:02:48.356
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:02:48.356 --> 00:02:52.960
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:54.550
DAVID WEITZ: Two lessons.

00:02:54.550 --> 00:02:56.690
If you're closer to the front, it helps.

00:02:56.690 --> 00:02:59.230
And if you come to the-- if
you come to the next lecture,

00:02:59.230 --> 00:03:02.290
you'll be all set for this quiz.

00:03:02.290 --> 00:03:04.240
Let me hand it back to Pia.

00:03:04.240 --> 00:03:05.530
PIA SORENSEN: OK, thanks Dave.

00:03:05.530 --> 00:03:09.829
So I thought we should
go into this lecture.

00:03:09.829 --> 00:03:11.620
So very soon, I'm going
to introduce Lidia.

00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:15.880
But I thought we should just
start pondering a few questions

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:18.880
that we can keep with us as
we go through the lecture.

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:22.610
And the question I want to
ask is, what is cooking?

00:03:22.610 --> 00:03:26.770
So when you cook, what is
the definition of cooking?

00:03:26.770 --> 00:03:27.760
Are there any ideas?

00:03:27.760 --> 00:03:28.480
No aprons.

00:03:28.480 --> 00:03:31.720
Well, actually, we have one apron left.

00:03:31.720 --> 00:03:33.640
Any ideas?

00:03:33.640 --> 00:03:35.740
What is the definition of cooking?

00:03:35.740 --> 00:03:39.125
All the way in the back.

00:03:39.125 --> 00:03:42.610
AUDIENCE: Altering raw
ingredients with heat.

00:03:42.610 --> 00:03:45.800
PIA SORENSEN: Altering
raw ingredients with heat.

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:46.895
Good.

00:03:46.895 --> 00:03:47.800
Any other ideas?

00:03:50.330 --> 00:03:51.172
Yeah?

00:03:51.172 --> 00:03:55.028
AUDIENCE: Altering the chemical
structure of ingredients so you can

00:03:55.028 --> 00:03:56.474
[INAUDIBLE].

00:03:56.474 --> 00:03:57.970
PIA SORENSEN: Uh-huh.

00:03:57.970 --> 00:04:01.300
Altering the chemical
structure of the ingredients.

00:04:01.300 --> 00:04:02.350
Anything else?

00:04:02.350 --> 00:04:03.662
Yeah?

00:04:03.662 --> 00:04:10.372
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] together
to make the food edible.

00:04:10.372 --> 00:04:11.080
PIA SORENSEN: OK.

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:12.270
Make the food edible.

00:04:12.270 --> 00:04:13.640
I like that.

00:04:13.640 --> 00:04:18.730
So if you go to the
Oxford English Dictionary,

00:04:18.730 --> 00:04:21.041
it says, "To prepare
or make ready food."

00:04:21.041 --> 00:04:23.290
So that's kind of along the
lines where you're saying.

00:04:23.290 --> 00:04:24.540
And then it mentions the heat.

00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:27.790
It says, "To make fit for eating
by due application of heat

00:04:27.790 --> 00:04:32.990
as by boiling, baking,
roasting, broiling, et cetera."

00:04:32.990 --> 00:04:36.400
So I would probably argue that
cooking is a very broad term.

00:04:36.400 --> 00:04:38.650
How you define it is kind
of a philosophical question.

00:04:38.650 --> 00:04:41.500
But the fact that you
apply heat, I think

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:45.200
that is one of the things that comes
foremost to mind for a lot of us,

00:04:45.200 --> 00:04:47.740
that you somehow add heat in some way.

00:04:47.740 --> 00:04:51.350
So that I want you to keep in mind.

00:04:51.350 --> 00:04:54.040
And the next question to
ask is, well, how much heat

00:04:54.040 --> 00:04:57.130
do you have to add to food to cook it?

00:04:57.130 --> 00:04:58.850
Like, when is it cooked?

00:04:58.850 --> 00:05:02.250
And I would say that this depends on--

00:05:02.250 --> 00:05:05.530
so you want to add some
heat to food, some cue.

00:05:05.530 --> 00:05:09.170
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:10.540 --> 00:05:12.340
That's barely an
equation, but thank you.

00:05:12.340 --> 00:05:14.998
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:16.987 --> 00:05:18.820
There is an equal sign,
so it's an equation.

00:05:18.820 --> 00:05:19.170
Good.

00:05:19.170 --> 00:05:19.520
Good.

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:20.020
Good.

00:05:20.020 --> 00:05:20.810
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:23.050
Good.

00:05:23.050 --> 00:05:23.962
So I would say--

00:05:23.962 --> 00:05:26.920
so if something is very big, you're
going to have to add a lot of heat,

00:05:26.920 --> 00:05:27.220
right?

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:29.928
If something's very small, you're
going to have to add less heat.

00:05:29.928 --> 00:05:33.366
So I would say that the
mass is important, right?

00:05:33.366 --> 00:05:36.840
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:36.840 --> 00:05:40.390
And then I would say, well, it kind
of depends on what kind of food it is.

00:05:40.390 --> 00:05:45.812
Let's say you're cooking pasta, or let's
say you're just cooking a marshmallow.

00:05:45.812 --> 00:05:47.770
They have very different
textures, so maybe you

00:05:47.770 --> 00:05:52.200
have to add different amounts of
heat to the food to make it cooked.

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:53.950
And for that in science,
we have something

00:05:53.950 --> 00:05:56.610
called the specific heat, which is CP.

00:05:56.610 --> 00:05:58.880
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:59.790 --> 00:06:02.480
See, you'll get tired doing this.

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:06.000
And then I would say, well, it depends
on how hot you want to make the food.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.240
So if you just want to heat it up
a little bit and make it lukewarm,

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:09.698
you don't have to add as much heat.

00:06:09.698 --> 00:06:11.750
But if you want to make
it really sizzling hot,

00:06:11.750 --> 00:06:13.208
then you have to add a lot of heat.

00:06:13.208 --> 00:06:16.739
So it depends on the
temperature difference, right?

00:06:16.739 --> 00:06:18.200
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:22.220
And now-- and now if I
put all of this together,

00:06:22.220 --> 00:06:24.890
I get the equation of the week.

00:06:24.890 --> 00:06:25.734
Now you clap.

00:06:25.734 --> 00:06:30.491
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:30.491 --> 00:06:31.990
So this is the equation of the week.

00:06:31.990 --> 00:06:34.370
And if you were a college
student in this class,

00:06:34.370 --> 00:06:36.950
you would now go into
lab, into our cooking lab,

00:06:36.950 --> 00:06:41.540
and you would explore this
question by cooking pasta.

00:06:41.540 --> 00:06:45.080
So the dish of the week
is pasta puttanesca,

00:06:45.080 --> 00:06:48.890
and we would ask all kinds
of questions about pasta.

00:06:48.890 --> 00:06:51.770
Pasta seems to be one of
those really basic things

00:06:51.770 --> 00:06:54.370
that most people have cooked, right?

00:06:54.370 --> 00:06:55.722
Right?

00:06:55.722 --> 00:06:57.680
But there are all kinds
of questions around it.

00:06:57.680 --> 00:07:02.630
So do you add salt to your water or not?

00:07:02.630 --> 00:07:04.190
How much salt do you add?

00:07:04.190 --> 00:07:05.820
Do you add the pasta--

00:07:05.820 --> 00:07:11.990
so how many here waits until the water
is boiling until you add the pasta?

00:07:11.990 --> 00:07:14.050
Who does not?

00:07:14.050 --> 00:07:14.840
Yeah?

00:07:14.840 --> 00:07:16.040
Why?

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:16.720
Why?

00:07:16.720 --> 00:07:17.220
Right?

00:07:17.220 --> 00:07:18.410
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:18.410 --> 00:07:20.045
I mean, it's just a question.

00:07:20.045 --> 00:07:21.110
It's just a question.

00:07:21.110 --> 00:07:22.650
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:22.650 --> 00:07:25.040
But questions you can
find the answer to.

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:29.510
So this lab was actually
born out of an article

00:07:29.510 --> 00:07:31.400
by Harold McGee, who was here last week.

00:07:31.400 --> 00:07:32.790
Who was here last week?

00:07:32.790 --> 00:07:33.290
Wonderful.

00:07:33.290 --> 00:07:37.190
So then you listened to
Harold talk about tea.

00:07:37.190 --> 00:07:40.910
But this is an article from
2009 in The New York Times

00:07:40.910 --> 00:07:43.110
where he asks the question--

00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:45.450
and this is another question related--

00:07:45.450 --> 00:07:50.180
so for example, when you cook
pasta, do you have a lot of water?

00:07:50.180 --> 00:07:52.260
Do you, like, fill the pot?

00:07:52.260 --> 00:07:55.430
Who just fills the pot
with a lot of water?

00:07:55.430 --> 00:07:56.450
I do.

00:07:56.450 --> 00:08:00.550
Who is, like, no, I just try
to take the bare minimum water?

00:08:00.550 --> 00:08:01.050
OK.

00:08:01.050 --> 00:08:03.280
So we're a bit more divided.

00:08:03.280 --> 00:08:07.289
So Harold asked this
question, and he said--

00:08:07.289 --> 00:08:08.080
let's see up here--

00:08:11.300 --> 00:08:15.170
why boil so much more water than
pasta actually absorbs, only

00:08:15.170 --> 00:08:16.340
to pour it down the drain?

00:08:16.340 --> 00:08:20.130
Couldn't we just cook pasta just as
well with much less water, less energy?

00:08:20.130 --> 00:08:22.550
Another question quickly followed.

00:08:22.550 --> 00:08:28.220
If we could, what would the
defenders of Italian traditions say?

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:35.200
So next he goes on and I described
my method in email messages

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:38.919
to two of this country's best
known advocates of Italian cuisine.

00:08:38.919 --> 00:08:43.690
Lidia Bastianich told me, my grandmother
would have thought of this idea

00:08:43.690 --> 00:08:47.470
surely as blasphemous,
but I think it's curious.

00:08:47.470 --> 00:08:50.830
And so she went into her kitchen,
and she actually did this experiment.

00:08:50.830 --> 00:08:56.950
And she finally concluded
that the cold water pasta-- so

00:08:56.950 --> 00:09:01.420
if you add the pasta to the cold water
and then you wait for the whole thing

00:09:01.420 --> 00:09:07.570
to start to boil, you boil it that way,
it had lost some of its nutty flavor,

00:09:07.570 --> 00:09:08.290
right?

00:09:08.290 --> 00:09:09.820
So she thinks, yes.

00:09:09.820 --> 00:09:13.870
I think it's good and doable to
reduce the cooking water by a third

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:16.090
from six quarts to four quarts.

00:09:16.090 --> 00:09:20.910
But please, (ITALIAN ACCENT)
put-a la pasta in boiling water.

00:09:20.910 --> 00:09:22.780
So there you go.

00:09:22.780 --> 00:09:25.120
So with this-- and
I'll show you this too,

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:28.600
because this is what we do in this class
here for those of you who were really

00:09:28.600 --> 00:09:30.530
into the structure of pasta--

00:09:30.530 --> 00:09:35.890
this is a graph of what pasta
looks like in a SEM microscope.

00:09:35.890 --> 00:09:37.690
This is dried pasta.

00:09:37.690 --> 00:09:39.970
This is pasta that has been--

00:09:39.970 --> 00:09:41.710
has been hydrated-- sorry.

00:09:41.710 --> 00:09:45.190
That has been-- what's the name?

00:09:45.190 --> 00:09:49.460
Cooked, hydrated,
rehydrated in 20 degrees.

00:09:49.460 --> 00:09:50.270
20 degrees.

00:09:50.270 --> 00:09:51.920
And this is 80 degrees.

00:09:51.920 --> 00:09:56.300
So you can actually, on the
microscopic scale, see a difference.

00:09:56.300 --> 00:09:59.560
I'd like to argue that
maybe chef Lidia could

00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:03.420
taste that difference with her mouth.

00:10:03.420 --> 00:10:06.790
So with this, I'm going here
is what we would do in lab.

00:10:06.790 --> 00:10:09.720
So with this, I'm going
to soon introduce Lidia.

00:10:09.720 --> 00:10:13.660
So this is very fitting
in a number of ways.

00:10:13.660 --> 00:10:18.120
For those of you who attended
this lecture series last fall,

00:10:18.120 --> 00:10:22.080
Eataly had just opened in Boston,
and we were all really excited.

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:25.950
And Mario Batali came and
gave the last lecture.

00:10:25.950 --> 00:10:27.630
Was anyone here?

00:10:27.630 --> 00:10:28.440
Yeah.

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:31.050
So I thought it would be
fitting now to start off

00:10:31.050 --> 00:10:34.950
this lecture series with Lidia
Bastianich, another co-founder

00:10:34.950 --> 00:10:36.090
of Eataly.

00:10:36.090 --> 00:10:41.580
Also the person behind Lidia's
Kitchen, Felidia, Del Posto,

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:44.640
many other restaurants.

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:46.650
And the other reason
this is very fitting

00:10:46.650 --> 00:10:53.280
is because what we're doing here
is we're applying heat, right?

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:57.170
In the first lecture by Harold
McGee and Dave Arnold, we cooked--

00:10:57.170 --> 00:10:59.640
Harold talked about tea, right?

00:10:59.640 --> 00:11:03.690
Very simple manipulation of
water to make a delicious drink.

00:11:03.690 --> 00:11:06.360
Dave Arnold talked
about sparkling water.

00:11:06.360 --> 00:11:11.760
Also very sort of simple manipulation
of water to make it delicious.

00:11:11.760 --> 00:11:14.820
Here we're going to add heat.

00:11:14.820 --> 00:11:16.800
I mean-- and some more things.

00:11:16.800 --> 00:11:20.360
But essentially, we're now
adding heat to our food.

00:11:20.360 --> 00:11:26.070
And we're doing it to a kind
of basic material in a way,

00:11:26.070 --> 00:11:28.110
just to grain, to rice grains.

00:11:28.110 --> 00:11:32.100
So as scientists, we like
to study simple systems,

00:11:32.100 --> 00:11:35.030
and I'd like to propose that
we're kind of doing that here.

00:11:35.030 --> 00:11:37.950
Although as you'll see, it's
actually very complicated.

00:11:37.950 --> 00:11:41.940
So with this, please
welcome Lidia Bastianich.

00:11:41.940 --> 00:11:47.341
[APPLAUSE]

00:11:56.670 --> 00:11:59.706
LIDIA BASTIANICH: Thank you.

00:11:59.706 --> 00:12:00.580
Thank you, professor.

00:12:00.580 --> 00:12:02.080
Thank you, professor.

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:04.310
Mia grazie for the invitation.

00:12:04.310 --> 00:12:05.360
Thank you very much.

00:12:05.360 --> 00:12:08.450
And it's a pleasure being here with you.

00:12:08.450 --> 00:12:09.580
Where are you two guys?

00:12:09.580 --> 00:12:10.540
Come on out.

00:12:10.540 --> 00:12:11.890
[LAUGH]

00:12:11.890 --> 00:12:13.650
So you know, we have--

00:12:13.650 --> 00:12:17.680
there's here the executive chef
of Eatily down at the Pru Center,

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:19.420
and his assistant Daniel.

00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:24.730
And we chose to make risotto today.

00:12:24.730 --> 00:12:27.130
And risotto's all about the technique.

00:12:27.130 --> 00:12:31.210
But you know, as she said, they
told me, well, you could cook.

00:12:31.210 --> 00:12:32.770
You can talk about it.

00:12:32.770 --> 00:12:34.514
You can taste things.

00:12:34.514 --> 00:12:37.180
And I says, how are we going to
have all these people look at me

00:12:37.180 --> 00:12:38.370
and not give them a tasting?

00:12:38.370 --> 00:12:39.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:39.310 --> 00:12:43.422
So we have the two of them,
which they're mixing the pots,

00:12:43.422 --> 00:12:45.130
so there will be a
tasting for everybody.

00:12:45.130 --> 00:12:45.850
Because I think--

00:12:45.850 --> 00:12:51.210
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:51.210 --> 00:12:56.560
Because-- because I think, you know,
yes, you listen to the technique

00:12:56.560 --> 00:12:59.870
and to the whys and to the
hows and answer the questions.

00:12:59.870 --> 00:13:02.170
But at some point, you know,
you've got to record it.

00:13:02.170 --> 00:13:05.090
You've got to record the flavor,
the textures, and all of that.

00:13:05.090 --> 00:13:07.306
So we made sure that you had that.

00:13:07.306 --> 00:13:10.250
So risotto.

00:13:10.250 --> 00:13:11.140
Risotto.

00:13:11.140 --> 00:13:12.740
What is risotto?

00:13:12.740 --> 00:13:17.920
Risotto is an Italian
technique of cooking rice.

00:13:17.920 --> 00:13:19.700
And it is a technique.

00:13:19.700 --> 00:13:25.420
It's considering Italian
culinary sort of sequence.

00:13:25.420 --> 00:13:27.056
It's a primo.

00:13:27.056 --> 00:13:29.860
A primo is usually a starchy dish.

00:13:29.860 --> 00:13:31.667
So you have dente pasta.

00:13:31.667 --> 00:13:32.750
Then you have your primos.

00:13:32.750 --> 00:13:36.910
It could be pasta, it could be
soup, and it could be risotto.

00:13:36.910 --> 00:13:42.270
And it is very much
appreciated by the Italians.

00:13:42.270 --> 00:13:45.820
And yes, it's in the
ingredients, but there's

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:48.850
so much in the technique
of cooking this dish.

00:13:48.850 --> 00:13:52.060
And once you have the technique
down-- and by today, you should--

00:13:52.060 --> 00:13:56.530
you can go home and
make any flavor risotto.

00:13:56.530 --> 00:13:59.210
And I'm pretty sure of that.

00:13:59.210 --> 00:14:00.840
So pay attention.

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:05.590
But what-- you know,
let's talk about rice.

00:14:05.590 --> 00:14:13.190
Rice is the one food that feeds
the most people in the world.

00:14:13.190 --> 00:14:20.530
There's records of 2500 before Christ
that rice was already being used.

00:14:20.530 --> 00:14:27.910
75% of the world cultures, the
cultures use rice in their meal.

00:14:27.910 --> 00:14:33.190
And rice is grown in every part
of the world except in every--

00:14:33.190 --> 00:14:35.260
except Antarctica.

00:14:35.260 --> 00:14:40.050
So rice is quite an important
element in our cuisine.

00:14:40.050 --> 00:14:41.680
There's more than 400 different--

00:14:41.680 --> 00:14:46.790
4,000-- no, 40,000
different species of rice.

00:14:46.790 --> 00:14:49.900
So you know, there's
a lot to select from.

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:55.840
The rice that we use for
risotto is the short grain rice.

00:14:55.840 --> 00:14:58.300
So you hear the word arborio.

00:14:58.300 --> 00:15:02.560
You hear the word
carnaroli, vialone nano.

00:15:02.560 --> 00:15:05.290
These are all specific kinds of--

00:15:08.690 --> 00:15:10.930
they're in the same
species, but there have

00:15:10.930 --> 00:15:12.830
little nuances and little differences.

00:15:12.830 --> 00:15:17.800
But all of them are for making risottos.

00:15:17.800 --> 00:15:23.740
And in Italy, which is the
largest country growing rice--

00:15:23.740 --> 00:15:27.520
the largest rice-growing
country in Europe,

00:15:27.520 --> 00:15:32.540
basically they grow
the short grain rice.

00:15:32.540 --> 00:15:39.730
So let's-- when did rice come to Italy?

00:15:39.730 --> 00:15:46.610
Rice sort of initiated in China,
Middle East, North Africa,

00:15:46.610 --> 00:15:51.080
and it crossed over into
Sicily about the 700s.

00:15:53.650 --> 00:15:59.850
Sicily, if you look at the Sicilian
recipe repertoire, you see rice.

00:15:59.850 --> 00:16:04.460
But rice, even though rice
grows in all parts of the world,

00:16:04.460 --> 00:16:09.260
Sicily wasn't the ideal
conducive to rain for rice,

00:16:09.260 --> 00:16:13.250
and rice slowly traveled
up to northern Italy,

00:16:13.250 --> 00:16:19.190
and it really gained a hold
in the 1200s up in Lombardy.

00:16:19.190 --> 00:16:22.610
Of course, Lombardy is the Po River
that comes down from the Alps.

00:16:22.610 --> 00:16:28.290
It has all its divisions, and
it's a great setting for rice.

00:16:28.290 --> 00:16:34.230
So the Po Valley, the Po Valley
starting from Lombardy into Piemonte,

00:16:34.230 --> 00:16:39.470
that is the area in Italy
where rice is really grown.

00:16:39.470 --> 00:16:49.160
Vercelli one of the cities is the
capital of rice growing in Italy.

00:16:49.160 --> 00:16:57.470
So what is the difference between
short grain rice and long grain rice?

00:16:57.470 --> 00:17:02.943
Now let me-- maybe I'll begin to cook so
that, you know, you get to the tasting.

00:17:02.943 --> 00:17:04.795
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:07.579 --> 00:17:12.890
Rice, one cup of rice will
yield two cups of risotto.

00:17:12.890 --> 00:17:17.599
It will take about 3 and 1/2 cups
of liquid to get there in about 17

00:17:17.599 --> 00:17:18.530
minutes.

00:17:18.530 --> 00:17:23.240
So the formula is not that complicated,
but everything else that comes in.

00:17:23.240 --> 00:17:28.930
What's important is that
you have some good stock

00:17:28.930 --> 00:17:32.480
to coax that starch out of that kernel.

00:17:32.480 --> 00:17:39.740
The stock, because rice, once it's
milled like this, rice has a bran.

00:17:39.740 --> 00:17:40.867
It's brown.

00:17:40.867 --> 00:17:41.450
It's a kernel.

00:17:41.450 --> 00:17:42.280
It's brown.

00:17:42.280 --> 00:17:44.000
And then it also has a germ.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:48.800
So when you look at the rice kernel,
and you see almost like a chipped tooth,

00:17:48.800 --> 00:17:51.635
that's the rice that has
been milled of its bran.

00:17:54.935 --> 00:17:58.160
The germ has been taken off.

00:17:58.160 --> 00:18:02.160
Germ is the food of the rice kernel.

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:03.080
So it has fat.

00:18:03.080 --> 00:18:04.580
It has nourishment.

00:18:04.580 --> 00:18:11.390
When you have brown rice, brown rice
has its bran on and it has the germ on.

00:18:11.390 --> 00:18:17.470
That's why brown rice oxidizes fast
on you, because it has the germ

00:18:17.470 --> 00:18:20.300
and it has the fattiness,
and it oxidizes.

00:18:20.300 --> 00:18:24.140
So brown rice, you keep
in the refrigerator,

00:18:24.140 --> 00:18:28.340
whereas regular rice keeps well
three months with no problem.

00:18:28.340 --> 00:18:31.910
The one thing, when you buy rice
and you run it through your hands,

00:18:31.910 --> 00:18:35.900
you don't want it to feel floury.

00:18:35.900 --> 00:18:41.460
You don't want the rice kernel to
have begun to open up, in a sense.

00:18:41.460 --> 00:18:43.370
Lose its starches.

00:18:43.370 --> 00:18:47.660
You want a nice dry kernel,
and it has the chip.

00:18:47.660 --> 00:18:49.220
That's perfectly fine.

00:18:49.220 --> 00:18:52.940
At that point, rice
has about 95% starch.

00:18:52.940 --> 00:18:58.790
So when we cook it, we need to add
the flavorings every step of the way

00:18:58.790 --> 00:19:00.470
to flavor that rice.

00:19:00.470 --> 00:19:04.160
And what we get out of
that rice is the texture,

00:19:04.160 --> 00:19:08.210
and it is that it absorbs
the flavor, and the flavor

00:19:08.210 --> 00:19:14.330
that we impart on the starches
that make the risotto creamy.

00:19:14.330 --> 00:19:19.490
So the first is to get
a nice hot stock, and it

00:19:19.490 --> 00:19:24.620
has to be hot at the same
temperature, you know?

00:19:24.620 --> 00:19:26.930
Heat, catalyst.

00:19:26.930 --> 00:19:29.000
You have a chemical reaction going.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.280
You put another
temperature, your stop that.

00:19:31.280 --> 00:19:33.620
And you do not want to do
that in this cooking process.

00:19:33.620 --> 00:19:35.400
You want to continue, continuously.

00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:38.060
You're coaxing up
those starches, and you

00:19:38.060 --> 00:19:41.870
want to continue at the same
temperature to add so it continues.

00:19:41.870 --> 00:19:48.401
But what you do need is a
wide pan like this so that--

00:19:48.401 --> 00:19:48.900
yeah.

00:19:48.900 --> 00:19:51.305
Am I speaking too close?

00:19:51.305 --> 00:19:55.980
So that as you're coaxing that
starch and add in the stock.

00:19:55.980 --> 00:19:58.730
The stock, you put it
in, pulls out the starch,

00:19:58.730 --> 00:20:01.220
and it evaporates, and
this process continues.

00:20:01.220 --> 00:20:04.880
So it's back and forth
of pulling that out.

00:20:04.880 --> 00:20:09.560
So a pan, a wide pan
with a nice thick bottom

00:20:09.560 --> 00:20:13.460
so that this heat is spread evenly.

00:20:13.460 --> 00:20:18.770
If you were to do it in this pan here,
you would have the rice up to here,

00:20:18.770 --> 00:20:22.250
and that rice wouldn't be at the
same temperature as the bottom rice,

00:20:22.250 --> 00:20:23.160
and whatever.

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:26.430
So a nice open-- and
this is a big portion.

00:20:26.430 --> 00:20:29.570
I'm going to make quite a bit of rice.

00:20:29.570 --> 00:20:35.100
If you make, you know, a
portion for four or six people,

00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:38.340
all you really need is two cups
of rice, three cups of rice.

00:20:38.340 --> 00:20:39.500
So you need a smaller.

00:20:39.500 --> 00:20:42.110
But that's important,
a constant temperature.

00:20:42.110 --> 00:20:45.280
And what I like wooden spoon.

00:20:45.280 --> 00:20:49.190
And you can get all in the corner
so that the starch doesn't scorch,

00:20:49.190 --> 00:20:53.970
because then you have another flavor,
another element, which you don't want.

00:20:53.970 --> 00:20:56.980
So we have the pan.

00:20:56.980 --> 00:20:57.760
The olive oil.

00:21:01.070 --> 00:21:01.880
Get olive oil.

00:21:01.880 --> 00:21:07.370
Let me raise the temperature here.

00:21:07.370 --> 00:21:15.980
And we'll-- you don't wash
the rice before cooking.

00:21:15.980 --> 00:21:21.560
The rice is milled, the bran
is off, and it is clean.

00:21:21.560 --> 00:21:24.200
In that package that
you get it, it is clean.

00:21:24.200 --> 00:21:25.360
So you do not wash it.

00:21:25.360 --> 00:21:27.710
You do not introduce
water, because then you

00:21:27.710 --> 00:21:33.230
begin already to break those starches
down, and you don't want to do that.

00:21:33.230 --> 00:21:34.170
So some oil.

00:21:34.170 --> 00:21:36.150
You guys are going to
do it on that side.

00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:41.070
Onions.

00:21:41.070 --> 00:21:42.980
I like a lot of--

00:21:42.980 --> 00:21:43.950
this is the flavor.

00:21:43.950 --> 00:21:47.450
So you can make a
risotto just with onions,

00:21:47.450 --> 00:21:50.870
like the risotto Milanese
that is made with onions.

00:21:50.870 --> 00:21:54.990
But the risotto Milanese has a
little bit of bone marrow in it

00:21:54.990 --> 00:21:56.480
and a little bit of saffron.

00:21:56.480 --> 00:22:00.920
But you can make a simple
risotto with the onion family,

00:22:00.920 --> 00:22:03.560
and then you can add the
different flavorings.

00:22:03.560 --> 00:22:13.840
So shallots and get
a little bit of salt.

00:22:13.840 --> 00:22:17.810
Salt. And if you notice
this, I'll go along.

00:22:17.810 --> 00:22:20.050
I'll salt as I go along.

00:22:20.050 --> 00:22:23.180
Right here I need salt,
because you want it--

00:22:23.180 --> 00:22:27.170
I want to disintegrate these
onions as soon as possible.

00:22:27.170 --> 00:22:29.480
I want to pull out the water in them.

00:22:29.480 --> 00:22:31.640
And of course, salt will do that.

00:22:31.640 --> 00:22:38.420
And I must say, this is fine salt. If
you want to do that, the flake salt,

00:22:38.420 --> 00:22:44.120
the bigger the kernel, the more
it pulls out of whatever you want,

00:22:44.120 --> 00:22:48.080
especially if you're
curing meats or something.

00:22:48.080 --> 00:22:54.135
The size of the salt is important
on pulling out those liquids.

