00:28:01.860 --> 00:28:09.340
Also if you take a look at rice, at
the kernel of rice and you look at it,

00:28:09.340 --> 00:28:11.610
you will see an opaque center.

00:28:15.320 --> 00:28:18.100
It's the core.

00:28:18.100 --> 00:28:21.220
And that, what that is, that
will give me an indication.

00:28:21.220 --> 00:28:25.560
But this is really fine tuning
how big that core is, that center,

00:28:25.560 --> 00:28:27.625
how packed the starches are.

00:28:27.625 --> 00:28:30.060
You know, so in the
center he has a lot of--

00:28:30.060 --> 00:28:35.630
so the wider that center is, the
more of the packed starches are.

00:28:35.630 --> 00:28:44.280
And the chances that the
rice will maintain its shape.

00:28:44.280 --> 00:28:48.980
So what the ideal risotto
is that the rice remains--

00:28:48.980 --> 00:28:52.240
it's thoroughly cooked,
but it's al dente.

00:28:52.240 --> 00:28:58.770
Al dente is the word to describe a
sensation, a feeling that for Italians,

00:28:58.770 --> 00:29:04.260
when they bite into their pasta or
into their risotto, the resistance

00:29:04.260 --> 00:29:05.110
against your--

00:29:05.110 --> 00:29:10.080
as Italians like that little
resistance in their mouth.

00:29:10.080 --> 00:29:11.850
But you know, it's
not just the Italians.

00:29:11.850 --> 00:29:13.290
Think about yourself.

00:29:13.290 --> 00:29:14.610
You love texture.

00:29:14.610 --> 00:29:17.250
You love-- celery has to be crunchy.

00:29:17.250 --> 00:29:19.380
Asian pear, nice and crunchy.

00:29:19.380 --> 00:29:26.130
So you know, an element in cooking and
in creating sensation is that tactile.

00:29:26.130 --> 00:29:31.260
We always talk about flavor and
aromas and taste, and so on.

00:29:31.260 --> 00:29:36.140
But the tactile element
of food is very important.

