I opened my first restaurant in '71.

00:48:58.390 --> 00:48:59.530
I was rather young.

00:48:59.530 --> 00:49:03.080
So it's been a long road in
restaurants for me, and I love it.

00:49:03.080 --> 00:49:05.320
I still have a good
time, as you can see.

00:49:05.320 --> 00:49:10.720
And along the way, those
restaurants and all the restaurants

00:49:10.720 --> 00:49:14.140
that we have now in Italy and all
of that, one of the great pleasure

00:49:14.140 --> 00:49:16.870
is precisely working with young people.

00:49:16.870 --> 00:49:20.090
Young people that are
enthusiastic, that are passionate,

00:49:20.090 --> 00:49:22.190
that are sweating over those stoves.

00:49:22.190 --> 00:49:25.510
And I think to myself,
then why are you doing it?

00:49:25.510 --> 00:49:30.970
I did it because, you know, I had to
do it, in a sense, and I loved it.

00:49:30.970 --> 00:49:34.980
But for me and evermore, you know,
as you grow into your profession

00:49:34.980 --> 00:49:40.900
and you kind of develop this collection
of information and maybe knowledge

00:49:40.900 --> 00:49:45.440
to share it, to cook with them, to
work with them, it is really wonderful,

00:49:45.440 --> 00:49:45.940
you know?

00:49:45.940 --> 00:49:48.400
And it's not that I have
time now to go everywhere .

00:49:48.400 --> 00:49:50.560
And plus, I have this Achilles tendon.

00:49:50.560 --> 00:49:53.080
If you didn't-- if you
saw me hopping around,

00:49:53.080 --> 00:49:56.392
my Achilles tendon is
ripped a little bit.

00:49:58.990 --> 00:50:02.530
So it's a pleasure to
work with you guys.

00:50:02.530 --> 00:50:07.180
I work with them on and
off, but now especially.

00:50:07.180 --> 00:50:14.036
But I come from a part of
Italy that is no longer Italy.

00:50:14.036 --> 00:50:16.380
I was born in Istria.

00:50:16.380 --> 00:50:19.240
Istria's a little peninsula.

00:50:19.240 --> 00:50:21.280
It was Italy.

00:50:21.280 --> 00:50:27.970
And after World War II, it was
given to communist Yugoslavia.

00:50:27.970 --> 00:50:36.220
And 350,000 ethnic Italians
actually left Istria back

00:50:36.220 --> 00:50:42.220
into Italy and into the world.

00:50:42.220 --> 00:50:45.550
I was just born, 1947.

00:50:45.550 --> 00:50:46.918
I'll tell you my age.

00:50:46.918 --> 00:50:48.550
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:48.550 --> 00:50:51.430
And that was just the--

00:50:51.430 --> 00:50:55.210
I was born, I think, three or four
weeks before the peace treaty.

00:50:55.210 --> 00:50:58.015
So my mother was expecting me.

00:50:58.015 --> 00:51:00.700
They decided not to go anywhere.

00:51:00.700 --> 00:51:03.760
Where are you going to go
in the world expecting?

00:51:03.760 --> 00:51:06.820
But I was born and the
Iron Curtain went down.

00:51:06.820 --> 00:51:12.250
And so my formative years,
I spent with my grandmother

00:51:12.250 --> 00:51:15.010
who remained there under communism.

00:51:15.010 --> 00:51:17.560
And the beauty of it was that--

00:51:17.560 --> 00:51:23.630
still is-- that my grandmother,
because food was scarce,

00:51:23.630 --> 00:51:27.670
was not all that available-- the
regime, the Iron Curtain went up,

00:51:27.670 --> 00:51:29.650
the regime was tight--

00:51:29.650 --> 00:51:32.440
and she had everything
to feed the family.

00:51:32.440 --> 00:51:36.730
We had chickens, we had
rabbits, we had two goats.

00:51:36.730 --> 00:51:38.710
Every year, she had three pigs.

00:51:38.710 --> 00:51:42.700
And you know, she grew everything.

00:51:42.700 --> 00:51:44.170
We made olive oil.

00:51:44.170 --> 00:51:46.090
Grandpa made a little bit of wine.

00:51:46.090 --> 00:51:47.350
We even grew our own potatoes.

00:51:47.350 --> 00:51:52.270
I remember, you know, going with her
to harvest the potatoes from the Earth.

00:51:52.270 --> 00:51:56.170
And she would pick up-- pluck--
because, you know, it's a bush.

00:51:56.170 --> 00:51:59.680
She would pluck it all up, take
the big potatoes off the roots.

00:51:59.680 --> 00:52:03.700
Mine was to collect the little
ones that was left in the dirt.

00:52:03.700 --> 00:52:08.110
And I still recall holding the
potato in my hand, and it was warm.

00:52:08.110 --> 00:52:10.750
It was warm as it had life.

00:52:10.750 --> 00:52:13.240
And you know, I can't get that out of--

00:52:13.240 --> 00:52:18.450
that connection of food
out of my system, you know?

00:52:18.450 --> 00:52:24.410
The appreciation that we should
have and my connection to food.

00:52:24.410 --> 00:52:25.910
So I work with--

00:52:25.910 --> 00:52:28.559
I cooked with, how we
used to have beans,

00:52:28.559 --> 00:52:30.100
eat them when they were string beans.

00:52:30.100 --> 00:52:30.760
They got bigger.

00:52:30.760 --> 00:52:31.426
We shelled them.

00:52:31.426 --> 00:52:32.920
That was for the winter.

00:52:32.920 --> 00:52:39.370
Even wheat, the kernels, she would
harvest, and we would have the kernels.

00:52:39.370 --> 00:52:42.100
She would keep them in
the canteen, as we said.

00:52:42.100 --> 00:52:45.730
And when she needed flour, we
would take two, three burlap bags,

00:52:45.730 --> 00:52:48.325
go to the mill, come
back with fresh flour.

00:52:48.325 --> 00:52:54.850
Now the flour was quite different,
because those kernels had the germ.

00:52:54.850 --> 00:52:56.770
You remember I was
talking about the germ?

00:52:56.770 --> 00:52:57.910
Had the germ.

00:52:57.910 --> 00:53:02.650
And so it had more flavor, more
nourishment, and more-- you know,

00:53:02.650 --> 00:53:08.530
sometimes you think why today
the flavors are different.

00:53:08.530 --> 00:53:10.180
Why?

00:53:10.180 --> 00:53:13.110
And it's those memories, you know?

00:53:13.110 --> 00:53:18.700
Collecting that cherry,
that fig, that perfect fig.

00:53:18.700 --> 00:53:24.130
It would hang, and it had almost,
like, stretchmarks on its skin.

00:53:24.130 --> 00:53:27.760
And it had, like, a drop of
honey on the bottom, nectar.

00:53:27.760 --> 00:53:28.870
I mean, I still remember.

00:53:28.870 --> 00:53:31.840
I go back, and I still
look for those figs.

00:53:31.840 --> 00:53:37.060
So I think that, you know, that
connection to food and to flavors

00:53:37.060 --> 00:53:38.730
stayed with me.

00:53:38.730 --> 00:53:46.360
And in 1956, my parents decided--

00:53:46.360 --> 00:53:47.920
I was nine something--

00:53:47.920 --> 00:53:51.250
that they could no longer-- my mother
was an elementary school teacher,

00:53:51.250 --> 00:53:52.810
my father a mechanic.

00:53:52.810 --> 00:53:55.240
And they just couldn't
continue to raise--

00:53:55.240 --> 00:53:57.310
and I have a brother
that's older than me.

00:53:57.310 --> 00:54:01.510
So they decided that they were
going to go back to Italy.

00:54:01.510 --> 00:54:04.660
But they didn't give you
permission to go back to Italy.

00:54:04.660 --> 00:54:05.770
You had to stay there.

00:54:05.770 --> 00:54:08.620
You couldn't get a visa or something.

00:54:08.620 --> 00:54:12.220
But we had family on the other side.

00:54:12.220 --> 00:54:17.680
So my mother decided that
my brother, myself, and her

00:54:17.680 --> 00:54:23.350
would go to visit Aunt Nina,
supposedly who was ill.

00:54:23.350 --> 00:54:27.850
And my father had to remain
as a hostage, in a sense.

00:54:27.850 --> 00:54:30.550
But two weeks later, he escaped.

00:54:30.550 --> 00:54:33.680
Actually, the border, the
barbed wire and the whole thing.

00:54:33.680 --> 00:54:35.440
Met us in Trieste.

00:54:35.440 --> 00:54:43.900
And in Trieste, we stayed with our
cousins, but also we stayed in Trieste.

00:54:43.900 --> 00:54:48.340
We couldn't depend and stay
there on another family's weight,

00:54:48.340 --> 00:54:51.166
as we called it.

00:54:51.166 --> 00:54:56.470
We entered-- my parents entered a
political refugee camp, San Sabba.

00:54:56.470 --> 00:54:58.740
Now it's a museum.

00:54:58.740 --> 00:55:01.320
And for two years, we were in that camp.

00:55:01.320 --> 00:55:07.270
And again, in that camp, waiting for
a possibility to migrate someplace.

00:55:07.270 --> 00:55:11.110
So you know, when you talk
about migration today, for me,

00:55:11.110 --> 00:55:17.650
it's very moving, and I
really feel what that meant.

00:55:17.650 --> 00:55:21.940
And there we were for two years
in there, almost like today.

00:55:21.940 --> 00:55:23.560
Where did we go for lunch today?

00:55:23.560 --> 00:55:25.336
We went to the--

00:55:25.336 --> 00:55:29.230
yeah, to the freshman
cafeteria, in line.

00:55:29.230 --> 00:55:30.970
I was in camp also in line.

00:55:30.970 --> 00:55:33.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:33.580 --> 00:55:34.330
Waiting.

00:55:34.330 --> 00:55:37.210
Waiting for food.

00:55:37.210 --> 00:55:40.060
But you know, when you have
these connections to food,

00:55:40.060 --> 00:55:43.930
really visceral from one to the other,
it just stayed with me, and it just--

00:55:43.930 --> 00:55:46.055
you know.

00:55:46.055 --> 00:55:48.190
Food for me is--

00:55:48.190 --> 00:55:52.330
because when we left
there, I didn't know

00:55:52.330 --> 00:55:55.150
that we were not going to
come back, and I had not

00:55:55.150 --> 00:55:57.370
said goodbye to my grandmother.

00:55:57.370 --> 00:56:00.100
So food was my memories.

00:56:00.100 --> 00:56:04.600
I would cook the flavors, the
thing that grandma taught me.

00:56:04.600 --> 00:56:10.270
And they remain my connection to her
and to the place where I was born.

00:56:10.270 --> 00:56:11.500
And I continue that.

00:56:11.500 --> 00:56:12.550
I did go back.

00:56:12.550 --> 00:56:16.210
I did see grandma after I was
married, so that was settled.

00:56:16.210 --> 00:56:23.170
But for me, at that age, because
in 1958, Dwight Eisenhower

00:56:23.170 --> 00:56:24.520
was the president.

00:56:24.520 --> 00:56:29.400
He opened-- we had a visa, and
we came to the United States.

00:56:29.400 --> 00:56:33.160
The Catholic Relief
Services brought us here,

00:56:33.160 --> 00:56:35.410
because we had nobody here either.

00:56:35.410 --> 00:56:36.481
We were kind of-- oh.

00:56:42.604 --> 00:56:43.930
There's the salt missing.

00:56:43.930 --> 00:56:48.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:48.750 --> 00:56:49.818
It Is.

